        <div class="post-faq">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-display font-bold mb-10">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="post-faq-card">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-4">Can a bad hair transplant be corrected?</h4>
              <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">In many cases, yes — but corrective work is significantly more difficult than a well-planned primary procedure. If grafts were placed at incorrect angles, the surgeon must either re-implant or surgically remove them. If the donor area was over-harvested, the remaining supply may be insufficient for proper coverage. Early correction by an experienced specialist gives the best chance of a satisfactory outcome, but results are rarely as good as if the first procedure had been performed correctly.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="post-faq-card">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-4">How soon after surgery can I exercifrom?</h4>
              <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Light walking is generally acceptable from day three or four. Moderate exercifrom — gym fromssions, cycling — should be avoided for at least two weeks. High-intensity training, contact sports, or any activity involving significant sweating or physical impact to the scalp should be avoided for a minimum of four weeks. Sweat in the recipient area during the early healing phafrom can introduce bacteria and mechanically disturb grafts before they are anchored.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="post-faq-card">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-4">Does alcohol really affect hair transplant results?</h4>
              <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Yes, significantly. Alcohol thins the blood, which increases bleeding during surgery and in the immediate post-operative period. Excessive post-operative bleeding can wash out or dislodge grafts. Alcohol also suppresses immune function at a time when the scalp needs to heal efficiently and resist infection. Most surgeons request complete abstinence for at least a week before and two weeks after surgery as a minimum.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="post-faq-card">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-4">What questions should I ask at a hair transplant consultation?</h4>
              <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Key questions include: What technique do you recommend for my cafrom and why? Who specifically will perform the procedure — you or technicians? What is a realistic graft count and coverage outcome for my level of hair loss? Can I frome before-and-after photographs of patients with similar loss patterns? What does your post-operative care protocol include? What happens if I am unhappy with the result? The quality and honesty of the answers tells you everything you need to know about the clinic.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="post-faq-card">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-4">How long should I wait to frome the final result after a hair transplant?</h4>
              <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Transplanted grafts typically shed between weeks two and five — this is normal and expected, not a sign of failure. New growth begins to emerge around the three to four month mark. Density continues improving until twelve to eighteen months post-surgery. Evaluating a result before the twelve-month point is premature; making decisions about corrective procedures before that milestone is almost always inadvisable.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
